text: A movie like this is essentially fantastic. I believe in everything Nazis were against. People of color DO make america a more culturally rich and special place and are just as good as white people. I love strong women too. And hurting others because they‚Äôre odd...who can deny thats awful? But heres the thing. On paper this movie is untouchable. Agree w all of it. I should be praising this movie as being extremely important and inspiring. But in real life many of these awful things..racism, bigotry, homophobia. They‚Äôre completely real and terrible. But there is a side of the political lane...a certain KIND of mindset...that is SO empathetic...so eager to right these wrongs...that they begin attributing every problem to them. And find them in everyone they dislike. The real life definition of racist, nazi, woman hater etc lose all power because everyone from your slightly un-pc uncle at a bbq to the latest pepsi ad is on trial and accused of being equal to the organized mass slaughter of an entire race. So...the real life political parallel then becomes clear in the film. And while all true and good hearted, the sane among us see it as the forced, blatant propaganda it is. Theyre using actual bad things as a tool to redefine whats bad about what they dont like...just like the nazis did. But the final nail in sanitys and reasons coffin is this....remember how on paper, separated from real life current day stuff, the movies absolutely right in its messages, forced or not? Well thats their teflon. If you criticize this film for being not subtle, saccharine, shmaltzy and condescending, or even just ‚Äúmeh‚Äù you are essentially saying a movie where different ppl are good n nazis are bad should not exist. Theyve got u. Ur a nazi. Ur a anti feminist. Ur alt right. I mean WHO ELSE but a straight up real deal racist would balk at a film like this? So we never win.....because its not about the content not being true. Its about the method of delivery, the real life political intent behind it, and the smug holier than thou spoonfed propaganda nature of it making what could have been a story of deep truth with an anti-hate crime stance we can all get behind, into the next last jedi-style debate where those who dont like it are toxic men and those who do are soy sipping trannies. Just tell a good story. Politics ruin literally. Everything. EVERYTHING. The End.

text: It's just fucking stupid and so lazy it may as well be a parody. It's Patch Adams tier crap.  In the documentary you got this really interesting twist, as you realize his little dioramas that appear just to be juvenile fantasies about sexy ladies, brave soldiers and evil nazis actually reflect his fucked up, sad life - that the Nazis soldiers are the regular workinig class dudes who beat him senseless after he came out to them etc.  I mean, it's an inbuilt metaphor. It's part of the real story. The writer doesn't even need to invent it - and they go ahead and LITERALIZE it.  Also;  >All dese stronk womyn, because womyn are so nice to me  ...He had lots of sexy ladies in his dioramas because he was a pervert who fetishsized women's clothing.  The title card "An Inspirational True Story" should have been a red herring - the true story is fascinating but tragic and depressing.  >I used to be a great artist, but now...  He was a severely mentally ill alcoholic cross dresser and loner. THEN he became an artist, after the beating.  I'm waitinig for the Disney take on the Henry Darger story.

text: Lot of bad information out there.  He's said repeatedly he doesn't remember the beating although it was almost certainly not actual neo-Nazis.  While he was indeed a cross dresser, he was a part time minimum wage weekends & holidays cross dresser who only did it in private and guess what?  So was J. Edgar Hoover.  He was also deeply in love with a number of woman who were indeed represented on his miniature and he depicted them saving him because psychologically, they did.  The women gave his life worth, not the dolls.  I think this might end up in the same category of films as Slingblade, The Straight Story, Unbroken.  and Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence.  Overlooked and passed up, but if you find it, you might be changed forever.

text: Lol at the comments getting offended by Nazis being portrayed in a bad light. Even if the guys that almost killed him weren't actual neo-Nazis, the portrayal in this film isn't that far of a stretch tbh. Also, conflating portraying Nazis in a bad light with portraying white people as a whole in a bad light is fucking retarded.

I believe that everyone is weird in their own way and as long as they're not hurting anybody that's generally okay. I'm also no fan of Nazis. But this made me cringe a lot. The combination of the main character's apparent sexual frustration and his violent fantasies just feels kind of... icky to me. The fact that they protect him and they're all kind of sexualized is kind of off putting to me as well.  I'm not here to tell anyone you're right or wrong if you like this or hate this, you can see it or not see it. And if you made this movie, I'm not here to tell you to change it, it's your baby. text: All the trash comments I'm seeing about how this film is propaganda or somehow implying the real guy deserved it make me sick. An alcholic Navy Vet was beaten nearly to death beacuse he admitted to cross dressing, woke up with no memory of his past and had to relearn how to do pretty much everything. The guy built this town to help cope with the trauma of nearly dying and decided to rebuild himself to be better than what he was before he almost died. And he's a pretty goddamn imagninative and talented artist. Maybe the movie will be oversentimentalized or poorly done, but the real story is amazing, and definitely not worthy of the targeting of bigoted fuckwads

text: Hi everyone, I'm Mark Hogancamp's niece. I've read a lot of the comments here and I see that a lot of people are wondering why they are using Nazis in this movie. They are literally taking Mark's life and turning it into a movie. He was attacked at a bar after telling some guys that he liked to wear women's clothes. He then used the dolls as therapy to help him recover from the trauma of the attack. He built a small town, which he called Marwencol, in his backyard and began photographing the dolls within the town. He created a whole fictional world based on his life and a lot of people he knows. He's very into WWII, so he used Nazis to represent the men that beat him at the bar. In the story he created, he and the people of Marwencol try to stop and defeat the "Nazi's." This helped him unleash the anger he had built up towards the men who attacked him, and it also helped him to regain control of his hands. Mark was always a very talented and creative guy, but the attack left him with shaky hands, and he had a very hard time making art. Years of doing this has helped him immensely, and he has started drawing again. I have not seen this film yet, but this film comes from a documentary about Mark called Marwencol. The documentary explains everything, and even tells Mark's fictional story that he created.  I hope this clears some things up.

text: This is so sad, but I feel like people are missing the real point of Mark's story, the political right sees it as "propaganda"(which it may or may not be) and the political left is using it as a tool to push a political agenda about "equality" and likely trans "rights" despite Hogancamp stating numerous times he is not trans and cross dresses partly for "pleasure." This isn't some fairy tale people should be praising it is a horror story about how America's mental health care system is completely broken. This poor man had his memory beat out of him, was in a coma for 9 days, woke up thinking it was 1984 and was essentially told to kick rocks by whomever was in charge of treating him, he was left to stew in his own without any memory of who he once was and became so delusional he created an alternate world to cope with his trauma out of necessity.  honestly I'd recommend watching the documentary "Marwencol" first because this movie is DEFINITELY not the real story it's the typical glossed over feel good Hollywood nonsense and the message it sends is pretty bad considering it's PG-13: if life is too much disconnect from reality(as if we already don't have a problem with suicide); that is the polar opposite of what should be done when one is troubled and it creates an environment inside one's self ripe for the generation of anger and resentment which may eventually lead to violence or suicidal thoughts. If you've suffered trauma please, PLEASE seek treatment, do not create a world for yourself like this to hide in, it may be painful now, but you will be much better off in the long run.  edit: regardless of my opinion I do feel like Hogancamp will be thrilled to see his world literally come to life on the big screen.

text: You know what is really fucking upsetting? That so many people of the right-wing - not even just the extremists - have begun blasting this movie for "spreading propaganda". They're literally being butt-hurt because a movie is trying to portray Nazis as bad.  1.) It's a movie and a lot of movies claim a creative license, so to speak, which allows them the ability and freedom to do things that aren't exactly close to the original storyline. That's fine. Plenty of historically inaccurate films are loved today. 2.) So when the film uses its creative license to blast Nazis, it's not trying to attack right-wingers, it's not trying to critique Trump, and it's not trying to be "anti straight white male". There is absolutely no correlation or reference to the Trump administration or to the stereotype that a lot of Republicans get for being "sexist, racist, homophobic Nazis". There is absolutely no evidence of that in the film or in its timing (don't you think they would've released that during Trump's inauguration time period rather than in the middle of his presidency to do that?) that it's trying to be "anti-Trump" or whatever shit you guys are coming up with. It's literally just trying to show that Nazis are bad people. And, in case you didn't know this before, they certainly are not good people. 3.) Why, in the loving hell, would you want to defend Nazis? Seriously. Logical, sensible conservatives would never in their right mind try to defend Nazis. The smart conservatives, not the alt-right shit trolls on Youtube, that I know of are well-spoken and give no reason for people to call them any stupid names or stereotypes, and this is coming from a left-leaning centrist. So why are the right-wingers and alt-right, the people who like to flaunt themselves as being more "patriotic" than the left, literally sympathizing with a manic, murderous group that was our enemy for a very, very, very long period of time? This seriously undermines all the sacrifices that many of our US Soldiers saw a century ago. If y'all be complaining about flag kneeling, then don't fucking try to back up Nazis. You're literally just picking and choosing different things to be "patriotic" about in order to fit your narrative.

text: ; The motion-picture is failing, because it's Social Justice Warrior, anti-white propaganda, e.g., Were the men who beat-up Mark Hogancamp neo-Nazis? NO!!! This is the movie's biggest fabrication with regard to the true story.  In real life, Mark's assailants did admit to beating him because he told them he was a cross-dresser, which would make it a hate crime, but they weren't actually neo-Nazi, white supremacists, as in the movie.  One of the real-life attackers, a 16-year-old nicknamed "Black Freddy," wasn't even white. DUH! However, to reinforce the artifice, the movie shows one of the men with a swastika tattoo on his bicep.  Please note, In the Marwencol documentary, and in the articles written about Mark Hogancamp, including in The New York Times, there was never a mention of his assailants being neo-Nazis. They also appear a bit older in the film.   In real life, two of the five attackers were teenagers.

text: Welcome to Marwen... The movie was just plain weird. Steve Carrell is great but the directing was garbage. There is a scene that really ticked me off. Mark is in court about to testify about the crimes that have been done to him. It had potential to be a heart wrenching, sad, and emotional scene. Instead, Marks doll character ‚ÄúHogey‚Äù starts fighting nazis and Mark crawls on the ground avoiding the crossfire (bullets). The movie was more about Marks dolls then actually Mark. I feel like i saw more of ‚ÄúHogey‚Äù then Mark himself. Not about overcoming his fears. The movie felt boring, i had no care on what the Marwen characters had to say because THEY ARE NOT REAL. They said based on a true story, they forgot to tell me 2/3‚Äôs of the movie is dolls fighting.  The movie also left plenty of questions unanswered. When Mark is in Wendy‚Äôs house, he notices a photo of a young child. It says something like ‚ÄúWe miss you‚Äù or ‚ÄúYou will forever be in our hearts‚Äù. But We never know what happend to the child and why it is included in the movie. The movie also didn‚Äôt tell us more about the side characters. The women of Marwen are Marks friends. But we never really go deep into who the characters actually are. Next, The movie ends with Mark and his good friend (Roberta) going out to eat some sushi, thats it. Nothing else, do they continue dating, do they end up marrying at one point? Lastly, this is my biggest frustration: In the end of the movie the film does not tell you what happens to the thugs that beat Mark up. Do they get a long sentencing? Do they get life in prison??? You wont know because they wont tell you. This movie is very confusing, making you wonder if it is Marks fantasy or real life. There was no music that moved you, no emotional scenes. Unlike the trailer, the trailer felt moving and had a wonderful soundtrack. Im just truly dissatisfied with this movie.

text: Hi everyone, I'm Mark Hogancamp's niece's sister. I've read a lot of the comments here and I see that a lot of people are wondering why they are using Nazis in this movie. They are literally taking Mark's life and turning it into a kino. He was attacked at a bar after telling some guys that he liked to wear women's clothes. He then used the dolls as therapy to help him recover from the trauma of the attack. He built a small town, which he called Marwencol, in his backyard and began photographing the dolls within the town. He created a whole fictional world based on his life and a lot of people he knows. He's very into WWII, so he used Nazis to represent the men that beat him at the bar. In the story he created, he and the people of Marwencol try to stop and defeat the "Nazi's." This helped him unleash the anger he had built up towards the men who attacked him, and it also helped him to regain control of his hands. Mark was always a very talented and creative guy, but the attack left him with shaky hands, and he had a very hard time making art. Years of doing this has helped him immensely, and he has started drawing again. I have not seen this film yet, but this film comes from a documentary about Mark called Marwencol. The documentary explains everything, and even tells Mark's fictional story that he created.  I hope this clears some things up.

text: Here's the deal...this guy built miniatures of a mythical town called, "Elgin Park" to cope with his being different from childhood. And this film seems written on his life somewhat. You watch the NATGEO thing and you decide. Very interesting sort of film, very interesting and unique artist of a man, Michael Paul Smith and his wonderful work. May he rest in peace forever for his photos of a town based on where he grew up, only better. Healing comes in so many forms in human life. I see the similarities. How we recover from life and it's trauma's is fascinating in scope. Haven't seen "Marwen" as yet, but on my list of films to eventually see. Perfect casting with Steve Carell too...who else could pull this off? Art parallels life sometimes folks. Think about it...
